    Iterates over a byte array containing a FIX message.

    The iterator returns the FIX fields directly from the byte array.

    This iterator is particularly useful if you want to process FIX messages while generating the minimum number of intermediate objects - such as Field objects or String objects.

    You normally iterate by calling the nextTag() method (or previousTag() if you are iterating backwards). For example: 

     FixBytesIterator iter = new FixBytesIterator(bytes, zoneStart, zoneLength);
 while (iter.hasNext()) {
   int tag = iter.nextTag();
   int valueStart = iter.getValueStart();
   int valueLength = iter.getValueLength();

   // Process the given tag, if necessary, using the bytes indicated
   // by valueStart and valueLength.
   // Note that we are working directly with the underlying byte array
   // here - no intermediate objects have been created so far.

 }
    You can also retrieve the current field value using various getValueAsX methods. Some of these methods create objects. However, getValueAsPositiveInt does not and is very efficient.
